# =============================================================================
# WHO READS THIS FILE
# =============================================================================
# Only the machine that runs this website (your VPS, laptop, or Vercel).
# Players and “customers” never edit this—they use the panel in the browser.
#
# Goal: let people run their Arma Reforger server from this app without opening
# the AWS website. You (the person deploying the panel) set secrets here once.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# A — Connect to a game server you already have (minimum for most setups)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Point SSH at the machine where Reforger is installed. Use a key that can log in.
#
# Required (all three concepts):
#   1) REFORGER_SSH_HOST — public IP or hostname of the game machine (must accept SSH from
#      wherever Next.js runs: your laptop, your VPS, or Vercel’s IPs if hosted there).
#   2) REFORGER_SSH_USER — Linux login (often "ubuntu" on Ubuntu images).
#   3) Private key — EITHER REFORGER_SSH_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH (file on the Next.js host) OR
#      REFORGER_SSH_PRIVATE_KEY (paste full PEM; on Vercel use \n between lines in the dashboard).
#
# Alternative: skip A and use only "Server setup" in the app (saved profile). If both exist,
# an active saved profile overrides these env values.
#
# Sanity check from the Next.js host:  ssh -i /path/to/key.pem -p 22 ubuntu@YOUR_HOST
# (same user/key as above). If that fails, the panel cannot connect either.

REFORGER_SSH_HOST=
REFORGER_SSH_PORT=22
REFORGER_SSH_USER=ubuntu

# Private key — pick ONE:
#   • Local dev: path to your .pem file
#   • Hosted (Vercel, etc.): paste the full key in .env / dashboard (multiline OK)
REFORGER_SSH_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH=
# REFORGER_SSH_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN OPENSSH PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END OPENSSH PRIVATE KEY-----"

# Paths on the *game machine* (defaults match a typical Ubuntu install)
REFORGER_SERVER_PATH=/home/ubuntu/arma-reforger
REFORGER_CONFIG_PATH=/home/ubuntu/arma-reforger/config.json
REFORGER_TMUX_SESSION=reforger
REFORGER_SERVER_CMD='./ArmaReforgerServer -config ./config.json -maxFPS 60'

# Optional: log file override, port shown on Home, short note on Home
# REFORGER_LOG_GLOB=
REFORGER_CHECK_PORT=2001
# REFORGER_INSTANCE_NOTES=
# REFORGER_ANNOUNCEMENT=

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# B — Optional: let the panel launch a new cloud machine (no AWS console for users)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# You add IAM keys here OR paste them once in the app (Servers → saved on this host only).
# If these are unset, the “Launch a new server” section stays in setup mode until configured.

# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# Optional: AWS_SESSION_TOKEN=   (temporary / assumed-role credentials)
# Optional: lock down who can reach SSH + game ports (default is open — tighten in production)
# AWS_PROVISION_SG_CIDR=0.0.0.0/0
# Optional: where app-saved keys live (default ./data/aws-credentials.json)
# REFORGER_AWS_CREDENTIALS_PATH=

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# C — Optional: where JSON files live on the Next.js host
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# REFORGER_ACTIVITY_LOG_PATH=      # default ./data/activity-events.json
# REFORGER_SERVER_PROFILES_PATH=   # default ./data/server-profiles.json

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Copy to ".env.local" for local dev. Never commit real secrets.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
